<subSubSection box="[151,845,1795,1822]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,845,1795,1822]" box="[151,845,1795,1822]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,845,1795,1822]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,845,1795,1822]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
Abundance of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1870" box="[325,498,1795,1821]" class="Hexactinellida" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Porifera" rank="class">Hexactinellida</taxonomicName>
off the Amazon River mouth
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="122" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1865,2030]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,151,352]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="122" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
The three species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="1870" box="[385,548,1865,1891]" class="Hexactinellida" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Porifera" rank="class">Hexactinellida</taxonomicName>
described here were rare to common at the central sector of the Amazon River mouth, off 
<collectingRegion box="[277,393,1900,1926]" country="Brazil" name="Para" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Pará State</collectingRegion>
, with only 
<specimenCount box="[518,672,1899,1926]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Moser &amp; Moraes &amp; Castello-Branco &amp; Pequeno &amp; Muricy, 2022" authorityName="Moser &amp; Moraes &amp; Castello-Branco &amp; Pequeno &amp; Muricy" authorityYear="2022" box="[710,1126,1899,1926]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Hyalonematidae" genus="Hyalonema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphidiscosida" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="alucia" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Cyliconemaoida">
<emphasis box="[710,839,1899,1925]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Hyalonema</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[856,1040,1899,1925]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Cyliconemaoida</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1056,1126,1899,1925]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">alucia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1133,1223,1900,1926]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1133,1223,1900,1926]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
being observed on a muddy sand bottom, 
<specimenCount box="[400,575,1934,1960]" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[610,865,1934,1960]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Dactylocalycidae" genus="Dactylocalyx" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pumiceus">
<emphasis box="[610,865,1934,1960]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Dactylocalyx pumiceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
widely spaced on rocky outcrops, and several specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Reiswig" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[249,499,1969,1995]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Farreidae" genus="Claviscopulia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sceptrulophora" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="facunda">
<emphasis box="[249,499,1969,1995]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Claviscopulia facunda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on coarse sand to gravel bottoms (
<figureCitation box="[892,1028,1969,1995]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,181,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-28@20.[160,1427,181,1747]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 14. Environment and populations of Hexactinellida off the Amazon River mouth, Northern Brazil. A, Hyalonema (Cyliconemaoida) alucia sp. nov. on muddy sand bottom off Pará State, 378 m depth; B, Claviscopulia facunda population on coarse sand to gravel bottom off Pará State, 250 m depth; C, Dactylocalyx pumiceus on rocky outcrop off Pará State, 260 m depth; D–F, Dense sponge community dominated by Dactylocalyx pumiceus on hard carbonate bottom off Maranhão State, at 170 m depth (D) and 180 m depth (E). Photographs by F. Moraes (A–C) and R. Moura (D–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332329/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">Fig. 14A–C</figureCitation>
). On the other hand, a dense sponge community dominated by a large population of 
<taxonomicName box="[683,822,2004,2029]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Dactylocalycidae" genus="Dactylocalyx" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="16" pageNumber="121" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pumiceus">
<emphasis box="[683,822,2004,2029]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="121">D. pumiceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recorded on the upper slope at the southern sector off 
<collectingRegion box="[190,365,151,177]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Maranhão State</collectingRegion>
, colonizing a steep hard bottom ramp partially covered by fine carbonate sediment (
<figureCitation box="[1291,1424,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,181,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-28@20.[160,1427,181,1747]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 14. Environment and populations of Hexactinellida off the Amazon River mouth, Northern Brazil. A, Hyalonema (Cyliconemaoida) alucia sp. nov. on muddy sand bottom off Pará State, 378 m depth; B, Claviscopulia facunda population on coarse sand to gravel bottom off Pará State, 250 m depth; C, Dactylocalyx pumiceus on rocky outcrop off Pará State, 260 m depth; D–F, Dense sponge community dominated by Dactylocalyx pumiceus on hard carbonate bottom off Maranhão State, at 170 m depth (D) and 180 m depth (E). Photographs by F. Moraes (A–C) and R. Moura (D–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332329/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Fig. 14D–E</figureCitation>
). Quantitative analysis of 
<quantity box="[419,508,185,212]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.832" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" unit="m" value="183.2">183.2 m</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[509,517,185,199]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">2</superScript>
of bottom imagery on the upper slope off 
<collectingRegion box="[981,1155,185,211]" country="Brazil" name="Maranhao" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Maranhão State</collectingRegion>
showed a total of 277 individuals of 
<taxonomicName box="[287,424,221,246]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Dactylocalycidae" genus="Dactylocalyx" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pumiceus">
<emphasis box="[287,424,221,246]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">D. pumiceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 99 of demosponges (mainly 
<taxonomicName box="[786,946,220,247]" class="Demospongiae" family="Corallistidae" genus="Corallistes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[786,906,220,246]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Corallistes</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
; voucher MNRJ 21293). The highest density of 
<taxonomicName box="[180,317,255,280]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Dactylocalycidae" genus="Dactylocalyx" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pumiceus">
<emphasis box="[180,317,255,280]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">D. pumiceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recorded between 170 and 
<quantity box="[664,734,254,281]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" unit="m" value="175.0">175 m</quantity>
depth, reaching 4.5 ind. 
<superScript attach="left" box="[994,1031,254,281]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">m-2</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[1042,1143,255,281]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,181,1747]" captionTargetId="figure-28@20.[160,1427,181,1747]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 14. Environment and populations of Hexactinellida off the Amazon River mouth, Northern Brazil. A, Hyalonema (Cyliconemaoida) alucia sp. nov. on muddy sand bottom off Pará State, 378 m depth; B, Claviscopulia facunda population on coarse sand to gravel bottom off Pará State, 250 m depth; C, Dactylocalyx pumiceus on rocky outcrop off Pará State, 260 m depth; D–F, Dense sponge community dominated by Dactylocalyx pumiceus on hard carbonate bottom off Maranhão State, at 170 m depth (D) and 180 m depth (E). Photographs by F. Moraes (A–C) and R. Moura (D–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6332329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6332329/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Fig. 14D</figureCitation>
). The maximum density of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,310,289,316]" class="Demospongiae" family="Corallistidae" genus="Corallistes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tetractinellida" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[151,271,289,315]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Corallistes</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
was recorded at 
<quantity box="[498,568,289,316]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" unit="m" value="220.0">220 m</quantity>
depth (1.5 ind. 
<superScript attach="left" box="[735,771,289,315]" fontSize="6" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">m-2</superScript>
). Considering the whole depth interval analyzed at this dive site (
<quantity box="[203,332,325,352]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.825" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.45" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" unit="m" value="182.5" valueMax="220.0" valueMin="145.0">145–220 m</quantity>
), 
<taxonomicName box="[351,607,325,351]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Dactylocalycidae" genus="Dactylocalyx" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="17" pageNumber="122" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="pumiceus">
<emphasis box="[351,607,325,351]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="122">Dactylocalyx pumiceus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
accounted for 73.6% of the total number of sponge individuals.
</paragraph>
